---
title: "Inversa"
---

Una matriz $A$ es no singular e invertible si existe una matriz $B$ de $n \times n$ tal que $A \cdot B = B \cdot A = I$.
La matriz B se denomina **inversa de A**

Sean:

$$
A =
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
2 & 3 \\
2 & 2 \\
\end{array}
\right] ; \quad
B =
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
-1 & \frac{3}{2} \\
1 & -1 \\
\end{array}
\right]
$$

Comprobemos que $A \cdot B = B \cdot A = I$.

1) $A \cdot B$

$$
a_{11}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
2 & 3 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
-1 \\
1 \\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= -2+3=1
$$

$$
a_{12}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
2 & 3 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{3}{2} \\
-1 \\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= 3+(-3)=0
$$

$$
a_{21}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
2 & 2 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
-1 \\
1 \\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= -2+2=0
$$

$$
a_{22}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
2 & 2 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{3}{2} \\
-1 \\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= 3+(-2)=1
$$

$$
A \cdot B =
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
$$

2) $B \cdot A$

$$
a_{11}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
-1 & \frac{3}{2} \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
2 \\
2 \\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= -2+3=1
$$

$$
a_{12}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
-1 & \frac{3}{2} \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
3 \\
2 \\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= -3+3=0
$$

$$
a_{21}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & -1 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
2 \\
2 \\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= 2-2=0
$$

$$
a_{22}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & -1 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
3 \\
2 \\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= 3-2=1
$$

$$
B \cdot A =
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
$$

Dado que $A \cdot B = B \cdot A$ podemos concluir que $B$ es inversa de $A$ y $A$ es invertible (no singular).

Si una matriz tiene inversa, la inversa es única.

La inversa de $A$ se escribe como $A^{-1}$ de forma que $A \cdot A^{-1}=I$ y $A^{-1} \cdot A=I$.

## Cálculo de la inversa 

Sea 

$$
A =
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 2 \\
3 & 4
\end{array}
\right]
$$

Para determinar $A^{-1}$, empezamos definiendola como:

$$
A^{-1} =
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
a & b \\
c & d
\end{array}
\right]
$$

Entonces

$$
A \cdot A^{-1}=
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 2 \\
3 & 4
\end{array}
\right]
\cdot
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
a & b \\
c & d
\end{array}
\right] =
I_2 =
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
$$

$$
A \cdot A^{-1}=
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
a+2c & b+2d \\
3a+4c & 3b+4d
\end{array}
\right]=
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
$$

De lo anterior obtenemos dos sistemas de ecuaciones que nos permiten encontrar los valores de $a,b,c,d$

$$
\begin{align}
a+2c &= 1 \tag{Sistema 1} \\
3a+4c&= 0 \\
\\
b+2d&=0 \tag{Sistema 2}\\
3b+4d&=1
\end{align}
$$

1) Sistema 1

$$
\begin{align}
a+2c &= 1 \\
3a+4c&= 0 \\
\\
a &= 1-2c \\
3(1-2c)+4c&=0 \\
3-6c+4c &= 0 \\
-2c &=-3 \\
\mathbf{c} &= \mathbf{\frac{3}{2}} \\ \\
a &= 1-2(\frac{3}{2}) \\
\mathbf{a} &= \mathbf{-2}
\end{align}
$$

2) Sistema 2

$$
\begin{align}
b+2d&=0 \\
3b+4d&=1 \\\\
b&=-2d \\
3(-2d)+4d &=1 \\
-6d+4d &=1 \\
-2d &=1 \\
\mathbf{d}&= \mathbf{-\frac{1}{2}} \\\\
b &= -2(-\frac{1}{2}) \\
\mathbf{b}&= \mathbf{1}
\end{align}
$$

Los valores de $a,b,c,d$ corresponden a los valores de la matriz inversa de A, recordemos que iniciamos definiendola como

$$
A^{-1} =
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
a & b \\
c & d
\end{array}
\right]
$$

Por lo tanto

$$
A^{-1} =
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
a & b \\
c & d
\end{array}
\right] =
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
-2 & 1 \\
\frac{3}{2} & -\frac{1}{2}
\end{array}
\right]
$$

Esta matriz cumple  con la $A \cdot A^{-1}=I$ y $A^{-1} \cdot A=I$

$$
A \cdot A^{-1}=
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 2 \\
3 & 4
\end{array}
\right]
\cdot
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
-2 & 1 \\
\frac{3}{2} & -\frac{1}{2}
\end{array}
\right]
$$

$$
a_{11}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 2 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
-2 \\
\frac{3}{2} \\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= -2+3=1
$$

$$
a_{12}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 2 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 \\
-\frac{1}{2}\\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= 1+(-1)=0
$$

$$
a_{21}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
3 & 4 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
-2 \\
\frac{3}{2} \\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= -6+6=0
$$

$$
a_{22}=
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
3 & 4 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 \\
-\frac{1}{2} \\ 
\end{array}
\right)
= 3+(-2)=1
$$

$$
A \cdot A^{-1}=
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
$$